1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Bb4+ 6. Nc3 O-O 7. O-O Nc6 8. e3
{[%cal Gd1e2,Gf1d1,Ge3e4] A)    white plan is to build the strong center after
Qe2 ,Rd1 and e4 ,} (8. Bg5 {B)}) (8. a3 {is the main line}) 8... Rb8 9. Qe2 (9.
Nd2 Na5) (9. a3 {Now it is better to exchange the bishop, otherwise White is
regaining the pawn.} Bxc3 (9... Be7 10. Qa4 b5 11. Nxb5 Bd7 12. Nc3 Nxd4 13.
Qxc4 Nb3 14. Rb1 c5 15. e4 Nxc1 16. Rfxc1 {White has a bit better chances}) 10.
bxc3 b6 11. Qe2 Na5 12. Ne5 c5 13. dxc5 Qc7) 9... b5 10. Rd1 {[%cal Ge3e4,
Gc1f4,Ga1c1] Diagram [#] White defends the "d4" pawn. next move is e4,
followed by Bf4 ,Rac1 with dangerous initiative for the sacrificed pawn.} (10.
e4 $6 Nxd4 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Rd1 Qb6 13. e5 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Nd5) 10... Nd5 $1 {
You should remember this idea! Knight goes to "d5" just before white gets
ready to play e3-e4.} ({In case of} 10... Qe7 11. e4 e5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Nxe5
Qxe5 14. Bf4 Qe7 15. a4 a6 16. axb5 axb5 17. e5 {White may count on growing 
activity which compensates the pawn  For example:} Bxc3 18. bxc3 Bg4 19. f3 Bf5
20. Qe3 Nd7 21. e6 (21. Ra7) 21... Qxe6 22. Qxe6 Bxe6 23. Bxc7 Rbc8 24. Bd6
Rfe8 25. Rdb1 {and White are at least equal}) (10... a6 11. e4 Bb7 12. Bg5 (12.
Bf4 Re8 13. a4 Ba8 14. axb5 axb5 15. Rxa8 Rxa8 16. Nxb5 Ba5 17. Qxc4 Qd7 18.
Rc1) 12... h6) 11. Bd2 ({of course not} 11. Ne5 $6 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Bxc3 13. e4
Bxe5 14. exd5 Qf6 $17 {Cvetkovic,S -Nikolov,J  Plovdiv BUL 2014}) (11. Ne4 {
has no sense as after} Be7 {White can't define his next step} (11... Qe7 12.
Bd2 e5 {was good enough Sarno,S -Miladinovic,I  Cannes 2005})) (11. Qc2 Be7 $1
12. a3 {other wise Nb4-d3} Na5 $1 13. Nd2 Nxc3 (13... a6 14. e4 Nb6 15. b4 cxb3
16. Nxb3 Nxb3 17. Qxb3 Bb7) 14. bxc3 Bd7 15. e4 c5 16. d5 exd5 17. exd5 Bd6 18.
Rb1 Re8 {with huge advantage for black}) 11... Be7 $1 {- now of the Black's
knights could reach the "d3" square via "b4".} (11... Nxc3 12. bxc3 Ba3 {is
unclear. In my opinion White should have a long-term compensation.  The game
Nilssen,J -Tiviakov,S  Turin 2006 followed by} 13. e4 Ne7 14. Rab1 a6 (14... c6
15. Ne1 Bd6 16. Nc2 Bb7) 15. Ne1 Ng6 $6 (15... c6 $1 $13) 16. h4 $1 {White
took the iniciative after Black misplaced his knight.}) 12. e4 (12. Ne4 {[%cal
Ga1c1,Gb2b3] is not logical as White blocks the "e" pawn. White's plan is Rac1
and b3.} Ba6 (12... f5 13. Nc5 e5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Bxc5 16. Ba5 Be6 {is
OK for Black.} 17. Rxd5 Bxd5 18. Rd1 Qe7 19. Bxd5+ Kh8 {and White compensation
for the exchange is rather dubious.}) 13. b3 Qc8 14. Be1 h6 (14... c3 {was
possible,but black prepared a trap}) 15. a4 $6 {the most logical continuation
but ...} (15. Nc5 Bxc5 16. dxc5 Rd8 17. Nd4 $13) 15... c3 $1 16. Bf1 {and now
the punishment} bxa4 $3 (16... Rb6 {in fact was good enough}) 17. Qxa6 Qxa6 18.
Bxa6 c2 {and black won in  Schaefer,M -Graf,A  Neustadt an der Weinstrasse 2008
} 19. Rdc1 axb3) (12. a3 {doesn't look good as it weakens the b3-square.  Now
Black will have  a safe square for his queen's knight on "b3". This little but
important detail is changing  the evaluation of the position in Black's favour.
} a6 (12... Nf6 {This is a very sofisticated way to use the the move a2-a3.
Just like in the main line, Black counts on the weakness of "b3".} 13. e4 Na5 {
and Black is fine - we arrive at similar position in the a3 line - the
difference is that White king's rook is on a wrong square.} (13... Nxd4 14.
Nxd4 Qxd4 15. Be3 Qe5 16. f4 Qh5 17. Qxh5 Nxh5 18. e5 {with unpleasant threats}
) 14. e5 $1 (14. Bf4 Nb3 15. Rab1 a6 16. d5 exd5 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Rxd5 Qe8 19.
Bxc7 Rb7 20. Bf4 Be6 21. Rdd1 Qc8 {and I prefer black here}) 14... Nd7 15. d5
Nb3 16. Rab1 exd5 17. Nxd5 Nb6 18. Nxb6 axb6 {I see  nothing decisive for white
}) 13. e4 Nb6 (13... Nf6 14. Bf4 Na5 15. d5 exd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Rxd5 Qe8 18.
Bxc7 Nb3 19. Bxb8 Nxa1 {is at least equal for black}) 14. d5 (14. Bf4 Bd6) (14.
Be3 Na5 15. d5 exd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Rxd5 Qe8) 14... exd5 15. exd5 Na7 16. Nd4
Re8 17. Bf4 Bd6 18. Qd2 Bd7 19. Bxd6 cxd6 $13) 12... Ndb4 $5 13. Be3 ({The
real test is the direct} 13. d5 exd5 14. exd5 (14. Be3 Bg4) 14... Nxd5 15. Ne1
$1 (15. Nxd5 Qxd5 16. Ne1 {[%csl Rc6,Re7][%cal Gg2c6] Black saves the piece
with} Qe5 $1 {[%csl Re2]}) 15... Nd4 (15... Nxc3 $2 {loses a piece due to} 16.
Bxc3 Qe8 17. Bxc6 Qxc6 18. Qxe7) 16. Qe5 $1 (16. Qe4 Nf6) 16... Nb6 $1 {this
defense is hard to find on the board} (16... Nxc3 17. Bxc3 Bf6 18. Qc5) 17. Be3
(17. Nxb5 $2 Bf6 18. Qh5 g6 19. Qc5 Nd7) (17. Bf4 Bf6 18. Qxc7 Qxc7 19. Bxc7
Bf5 20. Bxb8 Rxb8 $44) 17... Bf6 18. Qh5 g6 19. Qc5 Nd7 20. Qxa7 c5 (20... Nf5
21. Bf4 Nd6 22. Nd5) 21. Bf4 b4 (21... Rb6 22. Bc7 Ra6 23. Qxa6 Qxc7 24. Nd5
Qe5 25. Qa3 {is unclear}) 22. Bc7 Rb7 23. Qxb7 Bxb7 24. Bxd8 Rxd8 25. Bxb7 bxc3
26. bxc3 Ne2+ 27. Kf1 Nxc3 28. Rdc1 (28. Rd6 Nb5 29. Rxf6 Nxf6 30. a4 Nd6 31.
Bf3 Nfe4 32. Bxe4 Nxe4 33. a5 Kf8 34. a6 Ke7 35. a7 Ra8 36. Nc2 Kd7 37. Ne3 Nd6
38. Ra5 c3 39. Rxc5 Rxa7 40. Rxc3) 28... Nb5 {winning back the exchange, but
the positions is drawish.}) 13... Nd3 14. b3 {The outcome depends on the
destiny of the "d3" knight.} Ba6 15. d5 {critical position arised} (15. a4 bxa4
$1 16. Rxa4 Rxb3 17. Rxa6 Ncb4 18. Rxa7 Rxc3 $15) (15. Rab1 Qd6 16. d5 (16. a4
bxa4 17. bxc4 Bxc4 18. Qc2 a3) 16... Nce5 17. Bxa7 (17. Nxe5 Qxe5 18. Qc2 Bf6)
17... Ra8 18. Bd4 Nxf3+ 19. Bxf3 e5 20. Be3 b4 21. Na4 f5 $1 (21... cxb3 22.
axb3 Nf4 23. Qc2) 22. bxc4 ({the idea is in case} 22. exf5 cxb3 23. axb3 Rxf5
24. Be4 Nxf2 $3) 22... Bxc4 23. Qc2 f4 24. gxf4 Bb5 25. Nc3 bxc3 26. Rxb5 Nxf4
27. Bxf4 Rxf4 28. Qxc3 Qf6 29. Rd3 Rxa2 {with good winning chances for black})
15... exd5 (15... Bf6 16. dxc6 Bxc3 17. Rab1 {is in White's favour.}) 16. Nxd5
$1 (16. exd5 Na5 17. Qc2 Re8 18. Rab1 Nb4) 16... Bd6 17. a4 $1 (17. Ne1 Nxe1
18. Qxe1 Ne5 19. Bxa7 Ra8 20. Bd4 Nd3 (20... c5 21. Be3 Bb7) 21. Qe2 c6 22. Ne3
Re8 23. Nf5 Bf8 {I prefer Black.}) 17... bxa4 {only move} 18. bxc4 Nb2 19. Rdc1
f6 $1 {Diagram [#] avoiding white main threat e4-e5 and keeping all options
open} (19... Qe8 20. Nd4 Nxd4 21. Bxd4 Be5 22. Nxc7) (19... a3 20. e5) (19...
Nxc4 20. Rxc4 Na5 21. Raxa4 Bxc4 22. Rxc4 c6 23. Nc3 Nxc4 24. Qxc4 Qf6 25. h3 {
Very unclear position to me. The material balance is in Black's favour, but
all white light pieces develop great activity.}) (19... Na5 20. e5 Bxc4 21.
Rxc4 Nbxc4 22. exd6 Qxd6 23. Qc2 Nxe3 24. Nxe3 a3 25. Qa4 Qb4 26. Qxb4 Rxb4 27.
Rxa3 Nc4 28. Nxc4 Rxc4 29. Rxa7 g6 {should be an easy draw}) 20. Nd4 (20. Nd2
Na5) 20... Nxd4 21. Bxd4 a3 {The tension remains, White enjoys great activity,
but I  prefer black pieces - in case  of queen exchange, we  have clearly
better chances because of the strong passed pawn For example:} 22. Ne3 {idea
Nf5} Bb4 $1 23. Nd5 Bd6 $11 *

