1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Bb4+ 6. Nc3 O-O 7. O-O Nc6 8.
Bg5 {White's idea is to develop the bishop and to play e3 followed by Qe2. We
should mention, however, that piece exchanges are almost always in Black's
favour. White's  only chance of a succesfull attack is with all pieces on the
board.} h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. e3 (10. Rc1 Rd8 11. e3 e5 12. Nxe5 (12. d5 Bxc3 13.
Rxc3 b5) 12... Nxe5 13. dxe5 Rxd1 14. exf6 Rxf1+ 15. Bxf1 Bxc3 16. Rxc3 b5 17.
b3 Be6 18. bxc4 b4 19. Rb3 a5) 10... Rb8 $1 {From the time of my game against
Kozul in 2005 nothing has changed - White is stuggling to keep the balance.} (
10... Qe7 11. Qe2 $1 Na5 (11... Bxc3 12. bxc3 Na5 13. Ne5) 12. Ne5) 11. Nd2 Na5
12. Qc2 (12. Qh5 $6 Qf5 $1 {This move immedately puts an end to White's murky
initiative on the kingside.} (12... b6 13. Rac1 c5 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Nde4 Qe7
$11 {Kozul,Z -Delchev,A  Nova Gorica SLO 2005}) (12... b5 $5 13. f4 Qf5)) (12.
Qa4 Qe7 $1 13. a3 Bxc3 14. bxc3 b6 15. Qb4 c5 16. dxc5 Qxc5 17. Qxc5 bxc5 {
with much better endgame for Black.}) 12... Qd8 $5 $146 {Interesting novelty
found by J,Hjartarson in 2015, The idea is to leave the "e7" square for the
bishop.} (12... Qe7 13. a3 Bd6 14. Nce4 e5 15. Qc3 Nb3 16. Nxd6 cxd6 17. Nxb3
cxb3 18. Qxb3 {was only equal in Pelletier,Y -Bluebaum,M Zillertal AUT 2015})
13. a3 (13. b3 cxb3 14. axb3 b6) (13. Qa4 Qe7 $1 14. a3 Bxc3 15. bxc3 b6 16.
Qb4 c5) 13... Be7 $1 {preserving the bishop !!} (13... Bxc3 14. Qxc3 b6 15.
Nxc4) 14. Nce4 {In this position a powerful response at our disposal:} (14. f4
b5 15. Rad1 a6 16. d5 exd5 17. Nxd5 c6) (14. d5 b5 15. Rfd1 e5 16. h3 a6 17. g4
f5 $17 {Black starts his successfull kingside offensive in   Schaefer,M
-Hjartarson,J  Porto Mannu Palau ITA 2015}) 14... b5 $1 (14... f5 $5 15. Nc3 (
15. Nc5 $6 b6) 15... Bd7 (15... c5 $5) (15... b5)) 15. Rfd1 Bb7 16. a4 (16. Qc3
Bxe4 $1 17. Bxe4 c5) 16... Bxe4 17. Bxe4 Bb4 18. axb5 Bxd2 19. Qxd2 Nb3 20. Qc3
Nxa1 21. Rxa1 Rxb5 22. Rxa7 c5 $15 *

