1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Bb4+ 6. Nc3 O-O 7. O-O Nc6 8. a3
{I chose that move to be the main line, but I dont think that here White has
any chances to obtain an opening advantage, In fact, my opinion is that after
8.a3 Black enjoys mush easier life because of the possiblity to land his knigh
to "b3" via "a5".} Be7 9. e4 a6 $1 {[%cal Gc6a5,Ga5b3,Gb7b5,Gc7c5] Black's
plan is Na5-b3, b5, Bb7 folowed by c7-c5. This is the best move order as we
keep an eye on the "d4" pawn.} 10. Be3 ({In case White prefers more active
position for the bishop by playing} 10. Bf4 {, Black should respond with} b5 {
Now the only way is to sacrifice the "d4" pawn.} 11. Qc2 (11. Qe2 {- 117/179}
Nxd4 (11... Bb7 12. Rad1 Na5 13. h4 Nb3 14. Bg5 h6 15. Bf4 Re8 16. Rfe1 c5) 12.
Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Rad1 Qa7 14. e5 Nd5 (14... Nd7 15. Ne4 Nb6 16. Nf6+ gxf6 17. Bh6
f5 18. Rd4) 15. Nxd5 exd5 16. Bxd5 Bb7 17. Bxb7 Qxb7 18. Rd7 Rae8 19. e6 Qc6
20. exf7+ Rxf7 21. Rfd1 (21. Rxc7 Bf6) 21... Rxf4 (21... h6 22. Bxc7 $2 Rxf2 $1
(22... Qf3 {1/2 (34) Postny,E (2577)-Macieja,B (2639) Peristeri 2010})) 22.
gxf4 Qg6+ 23. Kf1 Bd6 24. f5 Qg1+ 25. Kxg1 Rxe2) (11. d5 exd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13.
Qxd5 Qe8 14. Bxc7 Ra7 15. Bf4 Be6 16. Qh5 Rd7 17. Ng5 Bxg5 18. Bxg5 Nd4 19.
Rad1 f6 20. Qxe8 Rxe8 21. Be3 Red8 $15) 11... Nxd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. e5 Nd5 14.
Rfd1 Qa7 15. Nxd5 exd5 16. Bxd5 Bb7 $11) (10. Qe2 Nxd4 11. Nxd4 Qxd4 12. Rd1
Qc5 13. e5 Nd7 14. Bf4 Rb8 15. Rd2 Qa5 16. Rad1 Nc5 17. Qxc4 b5 18. Qe2 b4 19.
Na2 Nb3 $11 (19... bxa3 20. b4 Rxb4 21. Nxb4 Qxb4 22. Rd4 $13 {1/2 (30)
Battaglini,G (2442)-Popilsky,G (2518) Israel 2013}) 20. Nxb4 Bxb4 21. axb4 Qxb4
22. Rd8 Bb7 {White is still a pawn down but he should be able to find the safe
path to the draw.} 23. Rxf8+ Rxf8 24. Bxb7 Qxb7 25. Rd7 Nc5 26. Rd4 Qb5 27. Qc2
a5 28. Be3 (28. Rc4 Nb3) 28... Rc8) 10... b5 11. Qe2 Bb7 12. Rad1 Na5 {We
arrived at the main position of the line} 13. Ne5 {Diagram [#]} (13. Bf4 Nb3 {
Black is completely safe here,   lets see how we meet all  White's attempts to
complicate the position:} 14. d5 (14. a4 b4 15. d5 bxc3 16. dxe6 Qe8 17. exf7+
Rxf7 18. Qxc4 Nc5 19. Ng5 cxb2 20. Rb1 Nfxe4 21. Qxf7+ Qxf7 22. Nxf7 Kxf7 23.
Rxb2 Bd5 24. Bxc7 Rc8 $15) (14. h4 c5 $1 {I like very much this aproach -
after completing development, Black imedaitely strives for active counteprlay
instead of "waiting to see" tactics.} 15. dxc5 (15. d5 exd5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17.
exd5 Bd6 $17) 15... Qe8 (15... Qc8 16. Bd6 Re8 17. e5 Nd7 18. Ne4 Nbxc5) 16.
Bd6 Nxc5 $15) (14. Rfe1 Re8 $1 {The preparatory move is always advisable.} ({
In case of the immediate} 14... c5 {White can reach a rather unclear position
after:} 15. d5 exd5 16. exd5 Re8 17. Qc2 Bd6 18. Rxe8+ Nxe8 19. Ng5 $13)) 14...
exd5 15. e5 (15. exd5 Bd6) (15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. exd5 Re8) 15... Nh5 16. Be3 g6
17. Nd2 Nxd2 18. Rxd2 c6 19. f4 Ng7 20. Qf2 f5 $17) (13. d5 exd5 14. e5 Ne8 15.
e6 c6 $1) 13... c5 $1 {Active counterplay!!} 14. d5 (14. g4 cxd4 $146 (14...
Qc7 {was in  Naoum,S -Maiorov,N  Paleochora 2012}) 15. Rxd4 Qc7 16. f4 Nb3 17.
Rdd1 Rad8 18. g5 Nd7 {and White has nothing concrete to show} 19. Nxd7 Rxd7 20.
Rxd7 Qxd7 21. Rd1 Qc7 22. e5 Bxg2 23. Kxg2 Rd8 24. Ne4 Rxd1 25. Qxd1 Qc6 26.
Qf3 Qd5 $17) (14. dxc5 Qc7 15. Bf4 Qxc5 16. Nd7 Nxd7 17. Rxd7 Rfe8 18. Rfd1
Rad8 19. Rc7 (19. Qf3 Bf6) 19... Qb6 20. Rdd7 Rxd7 21. Rxd7 Nb3 22. Nd5 exd5
23. exd5 Kf8 24. d6 Bxg2 (24... Bf6 $4 {Vogel,R -Maiorov,N  Travemuende 2012}
25. Qh5 $18) 25. Rxe7 Qd8 26. Bh6 Rxe7 27. dxe7+ Qxe7 28. Bxg7+ Ke8 29. Qxe7+
Kxe7 30. Kxg2 f6 31. Bh6 a5 $17) 14... exd5 15. exd5 (15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16. exd5
Bd6 17. Nc6 Qc7) 15... Qc7 16. Bg5 Rae8 $1 $146 {[%cal Ga5b3,Gb3d4] Diagram [#]
The plan is Na5-b3-d4} (16... Rad8 $6 17. Ng4 {created definite problems for
black in   Grachev,B -Gasanov,E  Dagomys 2010}) 17. f4 $1 (17. Rfe1 Nb3 (17...
b4 18. Na4 Bc8) 18. d6 Bxd6 19. Bxf6 gxf6 20. Qg4+ Kh8 21. Nd7 Rxe1+ 22. Rxe1
Bxg2 23. Qf5 Nd4 24. Qxf6+ Kg8 25. Qg5+ $11) (17. d6 Bxd6 18. Bxf6 Bxe5) 17...
Qd6 $1 (17... Nb3 18. d6 Bxd6 19. Bxb7 Bxe5 20. fxe5 Rxe5 21. Bf4 Rxe2 22. Bxc7
Re7 23. Rxf6 gxf6 24. Nd5) 18. Rfe1 (18. Qf2 Nb3 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Ne4 Qd8)
18... Nb3 19. Bxf6 (19. Qe3 Nd4 20. Bxf6 Bxf6 21. Ne4 Qd8 22. Nxc5 Nc2) (19.
Qf2 Nd4 20. Bxf6 gxf6 $1 21. Nc6 Bxc6 22. dxc6 Bd8 23. a4 b4 24. Nd5 c3 $1)
19... Bxf6 20. Ne4 Qd8 21. Qh5 {White pieces are very active, but we have
sufficient resourses to defend succefully.} g6 (21... Ba8 22. Nxf6+ Qxf6 23.
Nd7 Qxb2 24. Re5 h6 25. Nf6+ gxf6 26. Qg4+ Kh8 27. Rh5 Kh7 28. Qf5+ Kg7 $11)
22. Qf3 Bg7 23. Qf2 Qb6 $1 ({The exchange sacrifice leads to a draw.} 23...
Rxe5 24. fxe5 Bxe5 25. Nxc5 Nxc5 26. Qxc5 Qd6 {The endgame is level} (26... Bd6
27. Qd4)) (23... f6 24. Nc6) 24. Nd7 Qd8 25. Ne5 {With repetition. If White
takes the exchange, his position is bad.} (25. Nxf8 Kxf8 26. Kh1 Bd4 27. Qc2
Bxd5 $17) *

