1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Bb4+ 6. Nbd2 b5 $1 (6... a5 {
When Black supports  the "c4" pawn by means of b5 , White plays  Ne1 or Ne5,
forcing the answer Nd5 ( covering the weakened long diagonal ) when White is 
winining time for advance e4-e5  Thats how appeared the idea  to a5 prior to
b5, so in answer to Ne1 Black will move away his rook to "a6" or "a7"   Pay
attention  to the move order  6..a5 7 0-0 b5 transpose, but there is an
important difference:} 7. a3 $1 {Now Black should exchange his dark-squared
bishop.} Bxd2+ (7... Be7 8. Nxc4) 8. Qxd2 Bd7 (8... Ra6 9. a4 $44) (8... Nc6 9.
Qc3 Qd5 10. O-O Qb5 (10... O-O 11. Rd1 b5 12. Ng5 Qd7 13. a4) 11. Re1) 9. Ne5 (
9. Qc2 Bb5 10. Ne5 Nc6 11. Nxc6 Bxc6 12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. Qxc4 Qd5 14. Qxd5 cxd5
15. Bf4 Kd7 16. Rc1 Ra7 17. Rc2 Rb8 18. f3 Rab7 19. Kf2 Ne8 {is slightly
better for Black as his king is very active.}) 9... Bc6 10. Nxc6 Nxc6 11. Qc3 (
11. e3 e5 12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. dxe5 Ne4 $1) 11... Nxd4 12. Qxc4 O-O 13. Bf4 {and
White enjoys great activity in Bluebaum,M - Wells,P  London ENG, 2014.} Nc6 14.
Rd1 Nd5 15. Bxd5 exd5 16. Qxd5 $6 {this is enough only for a draw} (16. Rxd5 $1
Qf6 17. O-O $14 {was the obvious path to the advantage}) 16... Qe7 17. Qc4 Rfe8
18. Rd2 Rad8 19. Rxd8 Rxd8 20. Be3 Qe5 21. Qc2 Nd4 $11) (6... c3 7. bxc3 Bxc3
8. Rb1 {gives white full compensation. I dont like this kind of positions for
Black as he has no other choice but passively  watch White's growing activity.}
) ({Be aware that in case of} 6... O-O {White has a very strong option} 7. Qc2
{In this position, White has the following trap:} b5 8. a4 c6 9. axb5 cxb5 10.
Ng5 h6 11. h4 $1 {and Black should resign.}) 7. O-O a5 $1 ({In case of} 7...
O-O 8. a4 c6 9. Ne1 $1 {A great idea of the greek number one Ioannis
Papaioannou -} Nd5 10. Nc2 Be7 (10... Bxd2 $6 11. Bxd2 Bb7 12. e4 {without
dark-squared bishop Black's defense was problematic in  Papaioannou,I -Nielsen,
P  Eretria, 2011.}) 11. e4 Nc7 (11... Nb4 $2 12. axb5) (11... Nb6 12. e5 a6 13.
Qg4 {with dangerous iniciative}) 12. e5 Nd5 13. Ne4 {[%cal Gd1g4] followed by
Qg4 with great attacking prospects}) 8. a4 $1 (8. Nb1 {is too slow, Black has
a typical and a very strong stabilizing move:} a4 $1 9. Ne5 Ra6 10. a3 Be7 11.
Nc3 c6 12. e4 O-O 13. Be3 Nbd7 {and White had no compensation in  Kozul,Z
-Saric,A  Nova Gorica, 2007.} 14. f4 Nxe5 15. fxe5 Nd7 16. Qh5 Qb6 $1 ({in the
game was} 16... c5 17. Kh1 Qb6 18. dxc5 Bxc5 19. Bf4 b4 20. axb4 Qxb4 $17) 17.
Rad1 b4 18. axb4 a3 19. bxa3 Rxa3 $19) (8. a3 {makes no sense here} Be7 $1 9.
a4 (9. b3 cxb3 10. Qxb3 Ba6 11. Bb2 O-O $13 12. Ne5 Ra7) 9... c6 10. Ne5 {and
now in Fominyh,A-Alekseev,E Sochi 2004, Black played} Nd5 $15 (10... Ra6 $5)
11. Ne4 (11. b3 cxb3 12. Qxb3 Ba6 $15) 11... O-O 12. Nc3 (12. Nc5 f6 13. Nf3
Na6 14. Nxa6 Bxa6 $15) 12... Ba6 13. Qc2 (13. e4 Nxc3 14. bxc3 f6 $15) 13...
Ra7 14. Rd1 {and now was time for} f6 $15 ({or} 14... b4 {with an advantage
for Black.})) (8. b3 {is not working in this concrete position as after} cxb3 (
8... c3 9. Nb1 Bb7 10. a3 Be4 11. Ne1 Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Be7 13. Nxc3 $14) 9. Qxb3 (
9. Nxb3 a4 (9... Bb7 {is good enough here}) 10. Ne5 Ra7 11. Nc5 (11. Qd3 Nfd7
12. Nxd7 Nxd7 13. Nc5 O-O 14. Qxb5 Bc3 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. Qxd7 Bxd7 17. Rb1 Bxd4
18. Ba3 Rc8 19. Rfd1 c5) 11... Bxc5 12. dxc5 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Nd5 $11) 9... Bb7
10. a3 (10. a4 Bxd2 11. Bxd2 b4 $1) 10... Bd5 11. Qb2 Bxd2 12. Bxd2 c6 {
Black's concept for light square block proved  succesfull in  Porat,S- Horvath,
P  Budapest 2003} 13. Rfe1 Qb6 14. Rac1 Nbd7 15. Bg5 (15. Ne5 Bxg2 16. Kxg2
Nxe5 17. dxe5 Nd7 18. Be3 Qb7 19. f3 O-O) 15... O-O 16. Bxf6 Nxf6 17. Ne5 Bxg2
18. Kxg2 Rfc8 19. Qc2 Qxd4 (19... b4 $1 $15) 20. Nxc6 Qd7 21. Qc5 Qb7 22. Kg1 {
and now after} Kh8 $1 {Black could preserve a good winning chances.}) (8. Qc2
a4 $1 {is important idea to remember -from Kozul,Z -Palac,M  Zagreb 2004 black
prevents a4 and b3} 9. a3 Be7 10. Nb1 Bb7 11. Nc3 c6 12. e4 Nbd7 13. Re1 O-O
14. h3 Re8 15. Bg5 h6 16. Be3 Qa5 17. Rad1 c5 {with a clear advantage for
Black.}) 8... c6 9. Ne5 (9. b3 {is White's basic idea in such positions, In
case Black takes on "b3", white will recapture with the knight to take "c5"
under control.  The right reaction was demonstrated in the game Mikhalevski,V
-Roiz,M  Caleta 2011} c3 $1 10. Nb1 Bb7 (10... bxa4 11. bxa4 (11. Rxa4 c5 12.
Qc2 Bb7 13. Nxc3 cxd4) 11... c5 12. Qc2 Bb7 13. Nxc3 O-O) 11. Qc2 bxa4 12. bxa4
c5 13. Nxc3 O-O 14. dxc5 Nbd7 15. Nb5 Nxc5 16. Rd1 Qe7 {with an easy equality.}
17. Ne5 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Rac8 $11) (9. Qc2 {is the better version of the idea
with b3, White will first put the rook on "d1".} Bb7 10. Rd1 O-O 11. b3 c3 12.
Nb1 bxa4 13. bxa4 c5 14. Nxc3 (14. dxc5 Qe7) 14... cxd4 15. Nb5 (15. Nxd4 Bxg2
16. Kxg2 Bxc3 17. Qxc3 e5) 15... Nbd7 16. Nfxd4 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Rc8 $11) ({
Already} 9. Ne1 {is not that effective as before} Ra6 ({I think rook belongs
to a7 in this case when the pawn on "c6" is protected.} 9... Ra7 10. Nc2 Be7
11. e4 O-O 12. e5 Nd5 13. Qg4 Nd7 14. Ne4 f5 $1 $15) 10. Nc2 Be7 11. e4 O-O 12.
e5 Nd5 13. Ne4 Nd7 14. Qg4 f5 15. exf6 {And draw was agreed in Papaioannou,I
-Vidit,S Vrachati,, 2013, but I would prefer Black.} N7xf6 16. Qe2 Nxe4 17.
Bxe4 Bf6 18. Bd2 Ra7 19. Rfe1 Qb6 20. h4 b4 $1 $36) 9... Ra6 {This is the main
idea, I am following my game from 2011. Now I think that} (9... Nd5 {is good
alternative} 10. Ne4 (10. e4 Ne7 11. d5 O-O $1 12. Nxc6 Nbxc6 13. dxc6 c3 14.
bxc3 Bxc3 15. Ra2 b4 {broad black full success in  Miroshnichenko,E -Korneev,O
Khanty-Mansiysk 2005}) 10... O-O 11. Bd2 f6 12. Nf3 Na6 13. Nc3 Bxc3 14. bxc3
b4 15. e4 Nxc3 16. Bxc3 bxc3 17. Qc2 Nb4 18. Qxc3 Ba6 {and Black was fine in
Papaioannou,I -Malikentzos,S  Achaea, 2012.}) 10. Nb1 {The pawn on "d4" was
hanging.} (10. Ne4 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 f6 12. Nf3 O-O) 10... O-O 11. Bf4 (11. Na3 Qb6
) (11. Nc3 Rb6 12. Qc2 Bb7 13. Rd1 Nbd7 14. e4 Qc7 15. Bf4 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 Qe7)
11... Rb6 12. Nc3 (12. e4 Nbd7 13. Nc3 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Bxc3 15. bxc3 b4 16. Qe2
Ba6) 12... Nd5 13. Bd2 f6 14. Ng4 Bxc3 15. bxc3 b4 16. e4 Nxc3 17. Bxc3 bxc3
18. Ne3 Ba6 19. d5 cxd5 20. exd5 Rd6 21. Qd4 Nc6 22. Qc5 Nb4 23. dxe6 Rxe6 $19
{Krug ,R -Delchev,A Pamplona 2011  Nbd2 (2741) The Week in Chess 1093 [Ribli]}
