1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 c5 7. O-O $5 ({In
case White takes one move earlier,} 7. dxc5 Bxc5 {there is} 8. Na3 $5 {This
idea was successfuly tested in the game Giri,A -Van Kampen,R  Amsterdam, 2012.}
(8. Qa4+ Nbd7 9. Qxc4 b5 10. Qxb5 $6 Rb8 11. Qc4 Qb6 12. O-O Ba6 $17) 8... Ne4
(8... b5 $6 9. Nxb5 Qb6 10. Na3 Bxf2+ 11. Kf1 {leads to bad consequences for
Black.}) (8... Bxa3 9. Qa4+ b5 10. Qxa3 Bb7 11. O-O {with an excellent
compensation for the pawn in view of the complete control over the dark
squares.} a5 12. Qc5 Qd5 13. Qxd5 Bxd5 14. Nd4 b4 15. a3 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Ne4 17.
Bf4 $16) 9. O-O c3 $5 $146 {The only try to avoid White's domination.} ({
instead, the game followed by} 9... Nxd2 10. Nxd2 c3 11. Ne4 $1 Qxd1 12. Raxd1
Bxa3 13. bxa3 Ke7 14. Nxc3 {White had unplesant pressure in the endgame.}) 10.
Qa4+ Nd7 11. Qxe4 cxb2 12. Rab1 ({or} 12. Rad1 Bxa3 13. Bb4 Bxb4 14. Qxb4 Qe7
15. Qxb2 O-O) 12... Bxa3 13. Bb4 Bxb4 14. Qxb4 Qe7 15. Qxb2 O-O {It is out of
question that White has compensation for the pawn, but I dont think it is
enough for an advantage.}) (7. Bxb4) 7... O-O 8. dxc5 {A position with an open
center has arisen. In general, that is in White's favour as his Catalan bishop
will exert pressure on the long diagonal. Black should yet to solve the future
of his light-squared bishop. But White still needs to loose time to regain the
"c4" pawn.} Bxc5 9. Qc2 {the only way to capture the pawn without making any
serious concessions.} (9. Ne5 $6 Qc7 10. Bf4 Nh5 $15) (9. Na3 Bxa3 10. bxa3 Nc6
11. Rc1 e5 12. Rxc4 Be6 13. Rc2 Qe7 $11) 9... Nbd7 $5 {I think this is better
than} (9... Nc6 10. Qxc4 Be7 {which is a bit passive for Black, although White
should play very energetically to prove he has something real.} {better is} 11.
Qc2 $1 ({In case of the routine move} 11. Rd1 {, Black is at least equal after:
} e5 $1 12. Nc3 (12. Qc2 $5 Be6 13. Nc3 Qc8) 12... Be6 13. Qa4 Qb6 14. Ng5 {We
are following the game Aronian,L -Adams,M Plovdiv 2010} Ng4 $1 15. Rf1 {and
now Adams missed an interesting tactical oportunity:} Nxf2 $1 ({in the game was
} 15... Bxg5 16. Bxg5 $11) 16. Rxf2 Qxb2 17. Nxe6 Qxa1+ 18. Rf1 Qb2 19. Nxf8
Qxd2 20. Bxc6 bxc6 21. Qxc6 Rxf8 {and Black is a pawn up with good winning
chances.}) 11... e5 (11... Bd7 12. Nc3 Rc8 13. Rfd1 $14) 12. Bc3 Qd6 13. Nbd2
$36) 10. Qxc4 (10. Nc3 a6 $5 (10... Qe7 11. Na4 b5) 11. Bf4 Qe7 (11... b5 12.
Ne5 Nxe5 13. Bxa8 Neg4 {is leading to unclear position with unsufficient
compensation for the exchange.}) 12. Nd2 Nb6 (12... Nh5 13. Nxc4 Nxf4 14. gxf4
Nb6 15. Nxb6 Bxb6 16. Rfd1 Rb8 17. e3 Bd7 $11) 13. Bg5 h6 14. Bxf6 $1 Qxf6 15.
Nce4 $1 Qe7 16. Nxc4 Bd7 17. Nxb6 Bxb6 18. Qb3 Ba5 {looks like pretty equal
position. Melkumyan,H -Grachev EU-ch 12-th Aix-les-Bains 2012.}) (10. Na3 b6
11. Nxc4 Bb7 12. b4 Be7 13. Rac1 Rc8 14. Qd3 Nb8 15. Qxd8 Rfxd8 16. b5 Bd5 {
when White had to play carefully to keep the balance in  Rausis,I -Fridman,D 
Belgium BEL, 2015.}) 10... b5 $1 {Black's active counterplay is based on that
temporary pawn sacrifice.} 11. Qxb5 (11. Qh4 $6 Bb7 12. Nc3 Be7 13. Ng5 Bxg2
14. Kxg2 Rc8 15. Rfd1 Rc4 16. Qh3 Qb6 17. Kg1 b4 {Black took completely the
initiative in   Mikhalevski,V-Rotstein,A, Metz 2011}) 11... Rb8 12. Qd3 {
better than} (12. Qc4 Rxb2 13. Nc3 Rb4 $11 {Bindrich,F -Tari,A  Berlin GER 2015
}) 12... Rxb2 {the simplest} ({Black denied to regain the pawn in couple of
games , but in my opinion that decision is wrong} 12... Qb6 13. Nc3 $1 Ba6 14.
Qb1 Ng4 (14... Rfc8 15. Na4 Qb5 16. Nxc5 Qxc5) (14... Qxb2 15. Qxb2 Rxb2 16.
Na4 Rc2 17. Nxc5 Nxc5 18. Rfc1) 15. Qe1 Qxb2 16. Na4 Qb5 17. Nxc5 Nxc5 (17...
Qxc5 18. Rc1 Qd6 19. Rd1) 18. Nd4 $14) 13. Bc3 Rb8 (13... Rb6 {[%cal Gc8a6] is
an option, with Ba6 to follow. Let's see how the game may continue:} 14. Ba5
Ba6 15. Bxb6 (15. Qc2 Qc8) (15. Qd2 Ne4 16. Qe1 Qe7 17. Bxb6 axb6 18. a3 Ndf6
19. Nfd2 Bd4 20. Ra2 Nxf2 21. Rxf2 Ng4) 15... Qxb6 16. Qd2 Ne4 17. Qxd7 Nxf2
18. Rxf2 Qb2 $44) 14. Nbd2 Bb7 (14... Nd5) 15. Rab1 Qe7 16. Rb2 Rfd8 (16... Bd5
{was good enough in  Handke,F -Tari,A  Berlin GER 2015}) 17. Qb1 Bd5 {Black is
at least no worse} *

