GM Pavel Eljanov} O-O $1 ({The point is that in case of} 7... Bxd2+ 8. Nbxd2
cxd4 9. Nxc4 O-O 10. O-O Nc6 11. Rd1 Qe7 (11... h6 12. Qf4 Nd5 13. Qd2) 12.
Nxd4 Nxd4 13. Rxd4 e5 14. Rd1 h6 (14... Bf5 15. Nd6) (14... Bg4 15. Qe3) 15.
Qe3 {With typical pressure for White, Eljanov,P -Fedorchuk,S  Sibenik, 2009.})
8. O-O ({White has nothing in case of} 8. Bxb4 cxb4 9. Qxc4 a5 $1 (9... Qb6 10.
O-O Bd7 11. Rc1 Bc6 12. Ne5 $14) 10. O-O ({or} 10. a3 bxa3 11. Nxa3 b6) 10...
b6 $1 11. Rc1 Ba6 12. Qc2 Nbd7 13. Qd1 Qe7 14. Nbd2 Rac8 15. e3 e5 {with equal
chances in Ramirez Alvarez,A - Robson,R  Saint Louis, 2011.}) 8... b5 $1 {We
are following the recent game Cheparinov-Mamedyarov T-CH TUR 2015} 9. a4 ({
Instead, White can try} 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Ng5 {but Black's defense is not that
difficult} (10. Nd4 Bxd4 11. Bxa8 Qb6 $44) 10... Nd5 11. a4 h6 12. Ne4 Be7 13.
axb5 a6 14. Nec3 (14. Ba5 Qd7 15. b6 Nc6) 14... Bb7 15. Rd1 (15. bxa6 Nxa6)
15... axb5 16. Rxa8 Bxa8 17. Nxb5 Nd7 18. Qxc4 (18. e4 N5b6 19. Bf4 Qc8 20.
N1c3 Nc5 $11) 18... Ne5 19. Qd4 Qb8 20. N5c3 Bf6 $11) 9... Bb7 10. axb5 a6 $1 {
Black allowed White to regain the pawn, but now after complete liquidation of
the queenside pawns,, there will be nothing left to play for.} 11. bxa6 (11.
dxc5 {brings no advantage to white} Bxd2 (11... Bxc5 12. bxa6 Rxa6 13. Na3 Bd5)
12. Qxd2 axb5 $5 13. Na3 Na6 14. Nxb5 $5 Nxc5 $11 {Gupta,A -Akobian,V (2617)
Istanbul 2012}) 11... Rxa6 12. Rxa6 Bxa6 13. dxc5 ({Later Beliavsky improved
with} 13. Rd1 Qb6 (13... Nc6 $5 14. Be3 Qa5) 14. Bc3 (14. Ne5 $5 Bxd2 15. Nxd2
cxd4 16. Ndxc4 Bxc4 17. Nxc4 Qc5 18. Na3 Qb6 $11) 14... Nc6 15. e3 Bxc3 16.
Nxc3 cxd4 17. Nxd4 Ne5 {black had nothing to complain for in  Beliavsky,A
-Grandelius,N  Istanbul 2012}) 13... Bxc5 14. Nc3 Nbd7 15. Be3 Qb6 16. Bxc5
Nxc5 17. Ne5 Ncd7 {and draw was agreed} *

