1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. g3 dxc4 5. Bg2 Bb4+ 6. Bd2 c5 7. Bxb4 {This
move was recomended by Avrukh in his repertoire book from 2008.} ({In case of} 
7. O-O O-O {now} 8. Bxb4 {is leading to a favourable transposition for Black
compared to the main line.} cxb4 9. Ne5 (9. Qc2 a5 10. Qxc4 b6 {is good for
Black, Rahman,Z - Grandelius, N Tromso NOR, 2014.}) 9... Nc6 $1 $11 10. Bxc6
bxc6 11. a3 {and now the simplest is} Ba6 12. axb4 (12. Nxc6 Qb6 13. Nxb4 Rfd8)
12... Bb5 13. Na3 Qe7 14. Nexc4 Qxb4 15. Nxb5 cxb5 16. Ne5 a6 17. Qd3 Rfc8 {
with a comfortable equality.}) 7... cxb4 8. Ne5 (8. Nbd2 $6 {is just bad
because of} b5 $1 {Arun Prasad,S -Smerdon,D  Kuala Lumpur 2010}) 8... O-O {Now
White has two options - the move considered to be the best by Avrukh C1) and
C2) 9 a3! an amazing idea which could be the only source of headaches for
Black.} {C1) ]} 9. Nxc4 Nc6 10. e3 e5 $1 {A basic idea in this variation,
Black is immediately fighting against the center, opening up the diagonal for
his bishop "c8".} 11. d5 $5 {This was the Avrukh's main line. I agree  that
other options  are not better. In fact. now I think that even 11.d5 is not 
dangerous at all.} (11. dxe5 $5 Qxd1+ 12. Kxd1 Ng4 13. Ke2 $5 (13. f4 $6 {was
not correct as proved in  Sargissian,G-Moiseenko,A Moscow 2009}) (13. Bxc6 bxc6
14. Ke1 f6 $1 (14... Be6 15. Nbd2) 15. Nbd2 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 fxe5 17. Rc1 (17. e4
Ba6 18. Rc1 Rf6 19. f3 Rd8 $15 {Ashwin,J -Rosen,E  Las Vegas USA 2015}) 17...
Be6 18. Ke2 (18. f3 a5 19. Ke2 (19. b3 a4) 19... Bxa2 20. Rxc6) 18... a5 19.
Rc5 e4 $1 {Blagojevic,D -Grandelius,NPorto Carras 2011}) 13... Ngxe5 14. Nbd2
Bg4+ 15. f3 Bf5 16. e4 (16. Nxe5 Nxe5 17. f4 Bd3+ 18. Kf2 Ng4+ 19. Kf3 Nf6 20.
Rac1 Rfd8 $11) 16... Bd7 $1 {bishop may come back from b5} 17. Rhc1 (17. Nxe5
Nxe5 18. f4 Bb5+ $1) (17. Rac1 Rad8 18. Rhd1 f5 $1 ({or} 18... f6 $11) 19. f4 (
19. Nxe5 Nxe5 20. Rc5 Rfe8 $15 {Dzagnidze,N -Zatonskih,A Hangzhou 2011}) (19.
Nd6 $2 Nd4+ (19... Be6 20. Nxb7) 20. Ke3 Ba4 21. Nb3 Nxb3 22. axb3 Bxb3 23. Rd2
fxe4 $15) (19. b3 Nxc4 20. Rxc4 Be6 (20... Rfe8) 21. Rcc1 f4 (21... Rde8) 22.
gxf4 Rxf4 23. Ke3 Rh4 24. h3 Rf8) 19... Nd4+ 20. Ke3 Ng4+ 21. Kxd4 Ba4+ 22. Kc5
Nf2 $19 {and White should resign in Mikhalevski,V -Robson,R,  Philadelphia,
2011.}) (17. f4 $6 Nd4+ 18. Kf2 Ng4+ $17) 17... Rad8 18. Ke3 f5 $1) (11. Bxc6
bxc6 12. Nxe5 c5 {is obviously bad for White.}) (11. Nxe5 $6 Nxe5 12. dxe5
Qxd1+ 13. Kxd1 Ng4 14. Ke2 Nxe5 15. Rc1 Bg4+ 16. f3 Bd7 17. a4 Rac8 $15 {
Flores Rios,M       -Agdestein,S  Barcelona 2013}) 11... b5 $1 ({White would
keep a clear advantage after the knight retreat} 11... Ne7 12. e4 Ng6 13. O-O
b5 14. Ne3 $16) {Avrukh's main line is now} 12. dxc6 ({White's recent attempt 
for improvement was} 12. O-O $5 {but it faced the strong answer} Bg4 $1 {
Diagram [#] Black has other good options, but I like very much this
intermediate move} 13. Qd2 bxc4 14. dxc6 Qb6 {pawn on "c6" is going to fall.}
15. Qc2 (15. a3 a5 16. axb4 axb4 17. Rxa8 Rxa8 18. Qd6 e4 19. Rc1 Rd8 20. Qe7
Be6 21. Qb7 Rb8 22. Qxb6 Rxb6) 15... e4 $1 16. Nd2 (16. Qxc4 Rac8 17. Rc1 Rfd8
18. h3 (18. a3 $6 Rxc6 $1 {nice trick to remember} 19. Qxc6 Qxc6 20. Rxc6 Rd1+
21. Bf1 Bh3 22. Nd2 Rxa1 23. axb4 Rd1 {Black is winning}) 18... Be6 19. Qe2 Rd6
20. Nd2 Rdxc6) 16... Qxc6 17. Nxe4 Rac8 18. Rfc1 Bf5 19. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {and Black
was much better  in Guramishvili,S -Fridman,D  Rosmalen, NED, 2014.}) 12...
Qxd1+ 13. Kxd1 bxc4 14. a3 $1 (14. Nd2 c3 ({or} 14... Bg4+ 15. Ke1 c3 16. bxc3
bxc3 17. Nc4 e4 18. Nd6 Rad8 19. Nxe4 Nxe4 20. Bxe4 f5 21. Bg2 Rd2 {was equal
in  Lenderman,A -Sadorra,J Richardson 2012}) 15. bxc3 bxc3 16. Ne4 Nxe4 17.
Bxe4 Be6 18. Kc2 f5 19. Bg2 e4 20. Rhd1 Rab8 21. Rd6 Kf7 22. Kxc3 Ke7 23. Rad1
Rb6 24. f3 Rc8 25. fxe4 Rbxc6+ 26. Rxc6 Rxc6+ 27. Kb2 Rb6+ {and draw is
inevitable} 28. Ka1 Ra6 29. Rd2 Ra3 30. Re2 Bc4) 14... Bg4+ 15. Kc1 (15. f3 $6
Be6 16. axb4 Nd5) 15... a5 16. Nd2 Be6 $1 {big improvement over the line
pointed out by Avrukh.} (16... c3 $6 17. bxc3 bxc3 18. Nc4 e4 19. Rb1 Rac8 20.
Ne5 Rfd8 21. Rb3 $14) 17. axb4 {I  see no way for White to claim any advantage
here.} axb4 18. Kc2 Rac8 19. Ra5 Bf5+ {and White has nothing better than} 20.
